jor contractors. In my view this has the appearance of some kind of cartel in operation. They have clearly all decided, possibly in concert, to reject investment in a technology which would bring conside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rable benefits to the public purse and to road users and road workers. Ministers, Parliament and taxpayers rightfully deserve higher standards from the HA especially in dealing with issues where the public interest is so clearly at stake. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How will the </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment?</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Safety represents only a small part of the “Action for Roads” document and has been omitte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d from the specific terms of reference for this enquiry but it is a major issue of public concern and should be an integral part of the work of this enquiry; Statutory reportable incidents involving road workers have grown by a staggering amount according </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to recent figures:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#3333ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mr Fitzpatrick M.P., in a PQ in September 2012 [120374], was informed that there was a total of 47 road worker injuries during 2011 on motorways. Over a 3 year period from 2009 – 2011 there were 2 fatalities involving road workers on mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">torways.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/text/120912w0001.htm"><span style="color:#3333ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:sub">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/text/120912w0001.htm</span></a><span style="color:#3333ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">however, a recent press release from the HA states </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Eight road workers have been killed in the last three years and during the last 12 months there have been 1747 incidents where road workers were injured while improving and maintaining the strategic road network in England.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">Source:HA press release </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">21 Oct 2013. </span><a href="http://www.highways.gov.uk/news/press-releases/road-worker-tells-how-drunk-driver-careered-towards-them-on-the-m1/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:sub">http://www.highways.gov.uk/news/press-releases/road-worker-tells-how-drunk-driver-careered-towards-them-on-the-m1/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How can one account for this staggering increase? Was there systematic under-reporting for many years and, if so, why? Has there been a huge increase in recent times and why?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If implemented, “Action for Roads” states that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the HA seeks to develop:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> “technical innovations and behavioural measures to ensure road works are delivered safely.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(Page 48 Sect. 3.4.6)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Opportunities clearly exist for greater efficiency, “A single incident that closes a three-lane motorway for four hours can cost several </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">million pounds in lost time, and there are some 80,000 incidents that impact at least one motorway lane each year.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">(Source: Action for Roads – page 47 sect. 3.44)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in reality, new technology such as Conemaster has been systematically excluded from enterin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g the HA market since 2006 despite being independently assessed, even endorsed by the Minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">*</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“considerable safety and economic benefits”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the HA Network.</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> *</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">Letter to Dr McCrea from the Minister 9th July 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:8pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reducing congestion by an average of 30 minutes per closure through the mechanisation of cone laying and retrieval activities would significantly reduce emissions and, therefore, the carbon footprint across the Strategic Road Network. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How can we i</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">mprove the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will New Technology have on the Strategic Road Network?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Travel disruption caused by road maintenance is a big issue for the road user. Journey time reliability is directly impacted by these road closures. New technology such as Conemaster has been independently assessed by Jacobs to save at least 30 minutes pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r closure across the Strategic Road Network. Journey Time Reliability would be significantly improved, using Conemaster, for the 21% of road closures which take place during the day (between 6am and 8pm) and the 79% of closures at night (between 6pm and 6a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">Jacobs Report Feb 2012 Page15 - Sect 4.2.4 - Updated Lane Closure Information. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The Jacobs Independent Conemaster Review can be downloaded when this link is pasted into a web browser address bar: </span><a href="http://www.data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-1398/120378.doc"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-1398/120378.doc</span></a><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current Aiming for Zero Safety Strategy seeks to eliminate dangerous carriageway crossings by 2016. Carriageway crossings are frequently required to manually carry cones and lamps across often several live motorway lanes. Conemaster would all but elimi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nate such crossings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Mechanising dangerous manual handling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tasks has the capacity to remove road workers from the live lane whilst speeding up the manual handling tasks. The time workers and motorists are exposed to high risk would be significantly reduced. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Travelling at 15 mph working at rates of up to 40 cones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per minute,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">*</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Conemaster’s speed of operation reduces the time which road workers and motorists are exposed to high risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“…traffic cones will be laid and taken up quicker enabling more routine maintenance work to be undertaken during each closure so red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ucing the frequency of road works and congestion.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">*</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold"> Source: Transport Minister’s statement 2006 </span><a href="http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/new_cone_laying_machine_make_roadworks_safer/59291.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/new_cone_laying_machine_make_roadworks_safer/59291.html</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:baseline">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The adoption of new technology brings with it the potential to effect major efficiencies and cost control. This does not appear to have influenced either the HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s thinking or that of its major contractors. Collectively they appear content to accept the current inefficiencies and costs:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A Benefit to Cost Ratio of 2.06, independently assessed by Jacobs, makes Conemaster High Value for Money.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> An average saving across the Network of at least 30 minutes per road closure through the adoption of Conemaster has been independently assessed as valid by Jacobs. This would improve Journey Time Reliability across the Strategic Road Network for the 21% o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f road closures during the day (between 6am and 8pm) and the 79% of closures at night (between 6pm and 6am).*</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold"> *Jacobs Report Feb 2012 P15 - Sect 4.2.4 - Updated Lane Closure Information. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The Jacobs Independent Conemaster Review can be downloaded when th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">is link is pasted into a web browser address b </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-1398/120378.doc</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government policy to increase direct spend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with SME’s has the capacity to introduce competition into a market which is already averse to modernisation and investment in new technology.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform is required for procurement contracts in respect of SMEs to ensure that small companies are not exploited.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A TRL draft contract 2009 regarding a Conemaster trial sought the manufacturing and Intellectual Property Rights for Conemaster in bad faith for the benefit of the Crown. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 57.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The method by which Road Worker Safety is managed across the Network is deserving of major reform. For years, a flawed system has evolved which accepts significant conflict of interest between the HA and its major contractors. The Road Worker Safety Forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (RoWSaF), chaired by the HA, involves major contractors in the decision making process even though safety concerns and commercial interests are inevitably open to conflict of interest. This potentially allows powerful commercial vested interests to exerci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se considerable influence over any SME wishing to enter this lucrative market with a new innovative, HA-approved, safety-driven product.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in my view, this possibly explains the problem of the acceptance of poor data in respect of ‘reportable’ incidents, wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ich has meant that the true extent of “reportable” incidents has not been brought fully to the attention of Ministers and Parliament for many years. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following comments which were obtained under freedom of information put into context the serious need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for strong leadership combined with a fresh approach to road worker safety:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">i.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">”some activities are intolerable from an H&amp;S perspective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">” RoWSaF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Working Group Minutes 30-06-2011 Sect 4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> is no other area of work where it would be acceptable for people to work at such danger.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:sub"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">RoWSaF Working Group Minutes 30-06-2011 – sect 4.5</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">iii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“The HA had experienced a particularly bad year for injuries, across road workers and construction and maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> workers. The indication is that the situation has not improved and that in some areas it is worse. Data feedback indicates that many of these incidents are avoidable.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">RoWSaF Steering  Group Minutes  18-07-2011 – Ginny Clarke HA   Section 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee may wish to examine decisions taken regarding “cone laying machines” within the RoWSaF Trials Team minutes from 2006 to present. These minutes were robustly withheld from me under Freedom of Information by the HA, supported by the Department </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the grounds of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This raises </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further doubt and suspicion about RoWSaF’s decisions preventing the adoption of cone laying machines. It does not appear to be in the public interest. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:baseline">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A culture appears to exist within the HA where misle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ading information can be presented to support a pre-determined agenda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This dogged the early stages of the Jacobs review process. To gather accurate data required the use of freedom of information and the seeking of answers from the HA by my local M.P.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the HA’s handling of the Conemaster Cost Study </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">(29</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> June 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Jacobs Review would make a useful case study for the Committee to draw lessons regarding the HA’s poor control of Health &amp; Safety, maintenance costs and its approach to the introduction of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> innovative British technology.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There is a lack of transparency relating to important matters such as safety. Under-reporting of work-related incidents has existed across the HA Network for many years. Despite this, figures for road worker incidents did </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not show significant improvement. The Committee might wish to challenge why road worker incidents have escalated to 1747 over the past 12 months. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">(as discussed earlier in item 1.1 above)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under Freedom of Information, a HA audit report concerning Incident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Near Miss Reporting published 21-12-2011 found:  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Not all Agency staff are fully aware of reporting systems and the requirement to report incidents under RIDDOR legislation. There is under reporting of incidents by both Agency staff and contractors; a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nd some significant difficulties experienced by contractors in accessing and updating the AIRS database.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">  </span><a href="http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/116256/response/286424/attach/4/Incident%20and%20Near%20Miss%20Reporting%20redacted.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/116256/response/286424/attach/4/Incident%20and%20Near%20Miss%20Reporting%20redacted.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Conflicts of interest appear to exist between the HA and major contractors. The industry appears free to dictate cost, effici</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ency and even safety performance exhibiting the hallmarks of a cartel. From years of experience seeking to enter the HA market with an innovative British product, Conemaster is proof that SMEs have little chance of entering this important market. This is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pparent from the final paragraph of the Jacobs Independent Review regarding the possible adoption of Conemaster by major contractors. The final paragraph states: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This experience suggests some uncertainty as to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">extent to which the traffic management indu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">stry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">will adopt the machine and make sufficiently efficient use of it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to realise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">estimated benefits in practice.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Page </span><span style="